{
  "doc_id": "30600",
  "text": "To our knowledge, this is the first study evaluating the influence of acute resistance exercise on isoform-specific COX activity in human skeletal muscle. Our data support previous studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , which have indicated that COX-1 and COX-2 are expressed in resting skeletal muscle. As with previous work (5, 39) in human skeletal muscle, COX-1 protein content was not elevated with acute resistance exercise. In contrast, COX-2 protein was detected in all samples evaluated and was increased nearly five-fold 24-h postexercise. Contrary to our hypothesis, both COX-1 and COX-2 enzyme activity increased with acute resistance exercise; however, only COX-2 enzyme activity remained elevated at 24 h postexercise. The increase in COX-1 activity did not require an increase in protein levels, and changes in COX-2 activity did not correlate with changes in protein levels.",
